text: Current Microbiology  https://doi.org/10.1007/s00284-021-02557-y Taxonomic and Metabolomics Profiling of Actinobacteria Strains  from Himalayan Collection Sites in Pakistan Mohsin T. Cheema1,2,3 · Larissa V. Ponomareva2,3  Khaled A. Shaaban2,3  Received: 22 December 2020 / Accepted: 28 May 2021  © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer Science+Business Media, LLC, part of Springer Nature 2021 Abstract Actinobacteria have proven themselves as the major producers of bioactive compounds with wide applications. In this study,  35 actinobacteria strains were isolated from soil samples collected from the Himalayan mountains region in Pakistan. The  isolated strains were identified by polyphasic taxonomy and were prioritized based on biological and chemical screening to  identify the strains with ability to produce inimitable metabolites. The biological screening included antimicrobial activity  against Staphylococcus aureus, Micrococcus luteus, Salmonella enterica, Escherichia coli, Mycobacterium aurum, and  Bacillus subtilis and anticancer activity using human cancer cell lines PC3 and A549. For chemical screening, methanolic  extracts were investigated using TLC, HPLC-UV/MS. The actinobacteria strain PU-MM93 was selected for scale-up fer- mentation based on its unique chemical profile and cytotoxicity (50–60% growth inhibition) against PC3 and A549 cell  lines. The scale-up fermentation of PU-MM93, followed by purification and structure elucidation of compounds revealed  this strain as a promising producer of the cytotoxic anthracycline aranciamycin and aglycone SM-173-B along with the  potent neuroprotective carboxamide oxachelin C. Other interesting metabolites produced include taurocholic acid as first  report herein from microbial origin, pactamycate and cyclo(L-Pro-L-Leu). The study suggested exploring more bioactive  microorganisms from the untapped Himalayan region in Pakistan, which can produce commercially significant compounds. 2  Center for Pharmaceutical Research and Innovation,  University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY 40536, USA

3  Department of Pharmaceutical Sciences, College  4  Department of Natural Products Chemistry, School  5  Department of Neuroscience, University of Kentucky,  6  Ambystoma Genetic Stock Center, University of Kentucky,  7  Spinal Cord and Brain Injury Research Center, University  Institute of Microbiology and Molecular Genetics,  University of the Punjab, Lahore, Pakistan of Pharmacy, University of Kentucky, Lexington, KY 40536,  USA of Pharmacy, China Medical University, Shenyang 110122,  China of Kentucky, Lexington, KY 40536, USA  · Tao Liu2,3,4 · S. Randal Voss5,6,7  Actinobacteria are Gram-positive bacteria with complex life  cycle and are known as the major producers of bioactive  secondary metabolites, which are widely used as antimi- crobial and anticancer therapeutics along with many other  applications. They account for about 61% of the discovered  bioactive compounds of microbial origin, a major portion  of which is contributed by Streptomyces [1]. These bacteria  have been isolated and screened for bioactive compounds  from almost every type of environments, such as organic  matter rich soils, forests, desert ecosystems, drought effected  areas, freshwater bodies and marine ecosystems [2–6]. Due  to their complex life cycle, ability to produce exospores and  larger genomes dedicated to secondary metabolite produc- tion, actinobacteria can survive harsh climatic conditions  and produce variety of natural bioactive molecules. Microorganisms that inhabit extreme environments may  serve as a promising source of novel metabolites due to  gene expression modulation under specific climatic condi- tions [7]. Sampling from underexplored environments has  been demonstrated to improve the potential to discover both

novel microbes and their unique bioactive metabolites [8,  9]. Within this context, the great Himalayas span ~ 1400  miles with an average elevation of 6000 m and contain the  world’s tallest peaks. These mountain ranges separate central  and south Asia and primarily extend across the south Asian  countries of India, Nepal, Pakistan and a portion of China  [10]. The average temperature in summer varies from cold  to temperate and below freezing point in winter [11]. This  region consists of different types of landforms and plateaus,  and differs considerably with respect to altitude, rainfall, cli- matic conditions and soil composition, the soil is sandy loam  and loamy in nature which can retain moisture for longer  period and promotes forestation [12]. The region is enriched  with medicinal plants like Aesculus indica, Hypericum per- foratum and Cedrus deodara, Taxus baccata, etc., which are  endemic specie to this region and a key source of traditional  medicines used in the treatment of locals [13]. The Himalayan region in Pakistan is largely unexplored  in terms of actinobacterial diversity and microbial metabo- lite discovery. We recently reported Streptomyces from this  region to produce novel puromycins [14] new phenazine- based secondary metabolites (baraphenazines A-G) [15].  In the present study, we report the diversity of bioactive  actinobacterial strains represented among the samples from  Himalayan region in Pakistan along with the metabolomics  profiling and purification and identification of the cytotoxic/ antitumor compounds from a representative strain. The study  found strains from the genus Streptomyces to be the most  abundant and a small set of other slow growing rare act- inobacterial genera were also isolated. Similarly, this study  highlighted broad metabolite diversity consistent with that  of Streptomyces based on chemical profiling of the isolated  strains. The scale-up cultivation/fermentation, purification  and identification of the metabolites from one representa- tive Himalayan strain (PU-MM93) that exhibited notable  antimicrobial activity and cancer cell line cytotoxicity is also  reported.

The seven soil samples were collected in sterilized plastic  tubes from different sites [Muzaffarabad District, Kashmir  (coordinates: 34°21ʹ30ʹʹN, 73°28ʹ20ʹʹE); Naran, Mansehra  (coordinates:  34°54ʹ22ʹʹN,  73°38ʹ 58ʹʹE);  Kaghan  Val- ley, Mansehra (coordinates: 34°54ʹ17ʹʹN, 73°35ʹ00ʹʹE)] in  Himalayan mountains region, Pakistan (Table 1). The mini- mum distance between sample collection sites was at least  1–2 km. The samples were processed using methods given  by Hayakawa et al. [16]. Isolation of Actinobacteria Strains

The isolated actinobacterial strains were subjected to mor- phological,  microscopic,  biochemical  and  physiological  characterization. The species level identification was done  by 16S rRNA gene sequencing, for this, the genomic DNA  was extracted using DNA extraction kit (GeneJET, Thermo  Scientific, Rockford, IL, USA). The 16S rRNA gene was  amplified using the primers pair (27F, 5′-AGA GTT TGATC- MTGG CTC AG-3′; 1492R, 5′-GGT TAC CTT GTT ACG ACT  T-3′) [19]. QIAquick gel-extraction kit (Qiagen, Valencia,  CA, USA) was utilized to get gel-purify the amplified prod- uct. The amplified fragment for each strain was sequenced  utilizing the primers (forward and reverse). High-quality  sequences were assembled to produce the partial 16S rRNA  contig for each strain. NCBI server was used to check the  similarity for each contig against the available 16S rRNA  genes  data  to  determine  the  closest  homologs.  The  16S  rRNA gene sequence of the selected strains has been sub- mitted  in  the  NCBI  database  to  get  GenBank  accession  numbers (Table 1). For phylogenetic analysis, a neighbor- joining tree based on the 16S rRNA gene sequences of the  actinobacterial strains and their closely related type strains  was constructed at 1000 bootstrap replicates using Kimura  2-parameter model by Mega (version 6.06) software. Media optimization was performed to check the suitable  media for selected strain to get maximum production of  secondary metabolites using four different complex media  i.e., A-medium (glucose, 10 g; peptone, 5 g; yeast extract,  5 g; starch, 20 g; NaCl, 4 g;  K2HPO4, 0.5 g;  CaCO3, 2 g;   MgSO4.7H2O, 0.5 g in 1000 mL sterile water), F-medium  (sucrose, 100 g, casamino acids, 0.1 g; glucose 10 g; MOPS,  21 g; yeast extract, 5 g; trace elements, 1 mL;  K2SO4, 0.25 g;   MgCl2.6H2O, 10 g in 1000 mL sterile water), SG-medium  (soytone, 10 g; glucose, 20 g; cobalt chloride (III), 1 mg  inoculum  5 ×  105  cfu/mL.  Crude  extracts  (10  µM)  were  poured into each well of micro-titer plate and incubated for  16–48 h for antibacterial assay and up to 24 h for antifungal  assay. Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 6538 was maintained  on trypticase soy broth (TSB) at 37 °C. Micrococcus luteus  NRRL B-287 was cultured in trypticase soy broth (TSB) at  30 °C. Salmonella enterica ATCC 10,708, Escherichia coli  NRRL B-3708 and Bacillus subtilis ATCC 6633 were main- tained in nutrient broth at 37 °C. M. aurum ATCC 23,366  was maintained in Middlebrook with OADC supplement at  37 °C. Saccharomyces cerevisiae ATCC 204,508 was main- tained in YPAD media at 37 °C [21, 22]. Cancer Cell Line Viability Assay

The resazurin florescent assay was performed to determine  the cell viability of two cell lines including PC3 and A549.  The formation of fluorescent product resorufin from resa- zurin  (7-hydroxy-10-oxido-phenoxazin-10-ium-3-one)  was monitored in viability assay. The PC3 and A549 cells  (ATCC, Manassas, VA, USA) were grown in DMEM/F-12  Kaighn’s modification media (Life Technologies, NY, USA)  supplemented with FBS (heat inactivated), 10%; strepto- mycin, 100 μgmL−1; penicillin, 100 U  mL−1; l-glutamine,  2 mM. The 96-well culture plate (Corning, NY, USA) was  seeded with cancer cells at the density of 3 ×  103 cells per  well. Incubation of culture plates was done at 37 °C for  about 3 h. The fluorescence of resorufin was determined  with the help of a plate reader (FLUO star Omega, BMG  Labtech, Cary, NC, USA) with exciting and emission wave- lengths, 560 nm and 590 nm, respectively [21, 22]. Laboratory Scale Fermentation, Extraction  and Compounds Purification from Streptomyces sp.  PU‑MM93 The Himalayan isolate Streptomyces sp. PU-MM93 exhib- ited prominent in vitro inhibition of the tested cell lines, and  displayed interesting compounds based on TLC and HPLC/ UV studies, therefore, the strain was selected for scale-up  studies. The selected strain was refreshed using M2 agar  plates, incubated at 28 °C for 7 days. The seed culture was  prepared by inoculating a well grown agar piece into baffled  flasks (2 × 250 mL) containing 50 mL of A-media and incu- bated in orbital shaker (210 rpm for 2 days at 28 °C (Sup- plementary file, Fig. S3A, B). For large-scale fermentation,  A-media broth (10 L) was prepared and 100 mL broth was  dispensed in baffled flasks (100 × 250 mL) and autoclaved  (33 min at 121 °C). The 1 mL seed culture was inoculated  in each baffled flask containing A-media, separately. The  fermentation was performed on an orbital shaker for 10 days  at 210 rpm, at 28 °C.

For large-scale fermentation, 10 L of A-media broth was  prepared and was dispensed in 100 × 250 mL baffled bottles,  each comprising 100 mL broth, the flasks were autoclaved  (33 min at 121 °C). The seed culture about 1 mL was used  to inoculate every flask separately. The fermentation was  performed in rotatory shaker at 28 °C with the speed of  210 rpm for about 10 days. The fermentation process was  monitored by taking 1 ml fermenting broth on 5th and 7th  days, mixed with XAD-16N, followed methanolic extraction  and subjected for HPLC/UV analysis to evaluate the pro- duction level of the target metabolites. After 10 days incu- bation period, well grown reddish-brown culture was har- vested and centrifuged at 5000 rpm for 20 min for mycelium  separation. As shown in Fig. 1, the liquid phase (filtrate)  was mixed with XAD-16N (4% w/v) and kept overnight.  After filtration, the XAD-16N was washed with distilled  water (3 × 1000 mL). The XAD-16N resin was extracted  with MeOH (3 × 1000 mL). The solid phase comprising of  mycelium was extracted using MeOH (4 × 800 mL). The  crude extracts from mycelium and supernatant were pooled  based on their similar TLC and HPLC profiles. The  isolated  strains  showed  distinct  actinomycetes  like  morphological characteristics along with different size of  colonies. The colony size varied from 2 to 4 mm with regu- lar and irregular margins and different textures. The diffus- ible pigment was produced by some of the strains including  PU-MM54, PU-MM55, PU-MM57 and PU-MM67 (Sup- plementary file, Table S1). All the selected strains exhib- ited varying biochemical and physiological characters. All  selected strains were able to form melanin with the exception  of PU-MM67, PU-MM78, and PU-MM83; 60% of the iso- lated actinobacteria strains showed the ability to hydrolyze  urea, 71% hydrolyzed esculin, 19% utilized oxalate as their  only carbon source and 65% were able to form organic acid.  For sugar utilization, all selected strains utilized glucose effi- ciently, while 73% of the selected strains exhibited positive  growth on mannose, 63% on fructose, 60% on sucrose, 57%  on galactose and 55% of the strains exhibited growth on  mannitol (Supplementary file, Table S2). The  selected  actinobacterial  strains  were  also  identi- fied by sequencing their respective 16S rRNA genes. The  obtained sequences were analyzed and compared with those  available on NCBI database which showed the percentage  similarity with different actinobacteria type strains and rela- tive abundance on genus level. The genetic studies revealed  Streptomyces sp. as predominant among isolated actinobac- teria strains with only two isolates PU-MM63 (Nocardioides  sp.) and PU-MM86 (Lechevalieria flaviverrucosa) from  other genera (Table 1).

A neighbor-joining phylogenetic tree was constructed  by retrieving the sequences of isolated strains and most  closely relevant taxa from NCBI database. All the retrieved  sequences were aligned using CLUSTAL_W program. The  bootstrap value for most of the branches was high which  indicated high level confidence in tree topology. The phy- logenetic tree showed all the selected strains were members  of G + C rich order Actinomycetales. The actinobacteria  Fig. 2   Cytotoxicity of actinobacteria extracts against A549 (non-small cell lung cancer) and PC3 (prostate cancer) human cell lines strains  PU-MM71,  PU-MM83,  PU-MM58,  PU-MM78  and  PU-MM95  were  closely  related  with Streptomyces  rochei NRRL-B-2410T. All other strains were also mem- ber of genus Streptomyces except the strains PU-MM63 and  PU-MM86. The phylogenetic tree showed that PU-MM63  and PU-MM86 were distantly related with Streptomyces  and appeared on distinct branches in the tree. The strain  PU-MM63  and  PU-MM86  were  closely  related  with  Nocardioides caricicola  YC6903T and Lechevalieria terrae  NEAU-LZS  42T, respectively (Supplementary file, Fig. S1). In preliminary biological screening, actinobacterial crude  extracts were tested against human cancer cell lines for their  cytotoxic potential. The cells were exposed to hydrogen per- oxide  (H2O2) and actinomycin D as positive controls. The  crude extracts of selected strain PU-MM74 and PU-MM83  were highly toxic with 90% growth inhibition against both  cell lines. Actinobacterial strains PU-MM58 and PU-MM94  showed selective cytotoxicity against PC3 cell line with 63%  and 93% growth inhibition, respectively. The actinobacterial  strain PU-MM93 showed moderate growth inhibition against  PC3 and A549 cancer cell lines in the range of 40–50%  (Fig. 2).

Antimicrobial  activities  of  selected  actinobacterial  strains were evaluated against Gram-positive and Gram- negative test organisms. Actinobacterial strains PU-MM65,  PU-MM80, PU-MM82, and PU-MM97 were active against  S. aureus. In case of test organism M. luteus, actinobacte- rial strains PU-MM52, PU-MM57, PU-MM59, PU-MM61,  PU-MM65, PU-MM80, PU-MM81, PU-MM82, PU-MM87,  and  PU-MM97  showed  high  antimicrobial  activity  (Fig. 3A). The strains PU-MM52, PU-MM57, PU-MM61,  PU-MM65, PU-MM80, PU-MM81, PU-MM82, PU-MM87,  and PU-MM97 showed high antimicrobial activity against  Gram-positive  test  organism B.  subtilis.  In  case  of  test  organism M. aurum, the strains PU-MM65, PU-MM72 and  PU-MM82 showed high antimicrobial activity. The selected  Fig. 3   A Anti Gram-positive activities of generated extracts produced by the Himalayan isolated actinobacteria strains. B Anti Gram-negative  and antifungal activities of generated extracts produced by the Himalayan isolated actinobacteria strains actinobacterial strains PU-MM72 and PU-MM82 showed  high activity against both Gram-negative test organisms  E. coli and S. enterica. In antifungal activity screening,  PU-MM72, PU-MM80, PU-MM82, and PU-MM97 showed  the high antifungal activity (Fig. 3B).

The chemical profiling of the methanolic extracts by  TLC, HPLC/UV and HPLC/MS showed an enriched diver- sity of the metabolites produced by these actinobacterial  strains (Table 2). A variety of UV absorbing (254 nm),  florescent (365 nm) bands were observed on TLC, which  showed a range of different colors (including violet, blue,  yellow, orange and red) by staining with Anisaldehyde/ H2SO4 spraying reagent, suggesting the presence of com- pounds  belonging  to  different  structural  classes.  The  extract  of  strain  PU-MM63  exhibited  most  interesting  colored pattern on TLC by staining with Anisaldehyde/ H2SO4 reagent (Supplementary file, Fig. S2). Similarly  an array of diverse metabolites was detected in HPLC/ UV chromatograms at different wavelengths (210, 254,  280, 366 nm) with number of compounds showing peaks

at different retention times, with maximum visibility of  the  metabolites  at  254  nm.  The  HPLC/MS  analysis  of  the extracts suggested that the strains produce metabo- lites with molecular masses ranging in general from 150  to 800D with the most abundant masses in the range of  300–600D. However, some of the strains were found to  be producing the compounds with even higher molecu- lar masses, such as, in the extract of strain PU-MM57, a  compound with mass m/z = 1191 was detected, likewise in  the extract of strains PU-MM59 and PU-MM86, a com- pound with the mass m/z = 816 was detected (Table 2).  Based  on  the  chemical  profiles  of  the  extracts  along  with  their  bioactivity  analysis  the  six  strains  includ- ing  PU-MM57,  PU-MM59,  PU-MM63,  PU-MM82,  PU-MM86, PU-MM93 were selected as priority strains in  the collection. Herein, we have selected one of the priority  strains “PU-MM93” for the scale-up studies, including the  fermentation, extraction and purification/structure deter- mination of the secondary metabolites produced by the  Himalayan isolate Streptomyces PU-MM93. Actinobacteria  are  renowned  producers  of  biologically  active metabolites and contribute about 60–70% approved  drugs which are formulated with natural product-based skel- eton [28]. The recent decline in discovery of new bioactive  metabolites requires expanded efforts to probe untapped and  unexplored habitats [29]. The current study focused on actin- omycetes from the unexplored Himalayan region in Pakistan  that has recently led to the discovery of new bioactive micro- bial metabolites [14, 15]. The isolated actinobacterial strains  from this study were identified on the basis of morphologi- cal, biochemical and genetic characterization. The selected  strains displayed diverse morphology and biochemical char- acteristics (Supplementary file, Table S1) which indicated  that the strains are different actinobacteria species and the  genetic characterization further proved it (Table 1). The iso- lated actinobacteria strains displayed the ability to use broad  range of sugars as carbon source which is another hallmark  of Streptomyces sp. as reported by Bajaj and Sharma [30].  The phylogenetic analysis revealed that most of the selected  strains belonged to order Streptomycetales, mainly the mem- bers of genus Streptomyces, while some strains belonged to  rare genera including Nocardioides and Lechevalieria, such  as the strains PU-MM63 and PU-MM86. The  crude  extracts  of  isolated  actinobacterial  strains  exhibited significant cytotoxicity against two human can- cer cell lines A549 and PC3 (Fig. 2) and showed promising  antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive and Gram-neg- ative test microorganisms along with antifungal activities  against Saccharomyces cerevisiae (Fig. 3A, B). Some of the  strains showed broad spectrum antimicrobial activities but  some isolates showed selective activities. It was clear from  the results that most of the strains were strongly inhibiting  Gram-positive test strains, these findings are in line with the

study conducted by Li et al. [31]. Overall, 40% of actinobac- terial strains showed bioactivity against at least one of the  test organism/ cancer cell line. Among the 35 screened strain  11  strains  (31%)  were  active  against  Gram-positive  test  strains, 4 strains (11%) were active against Gram-negative  test strains and 6 strains (17%) exhibited significant cytotox- icity (above 50% cell mortality). The chemical profiling of  the extracts of selected strains by TLC, HPLC and LC–MS  analyses indicated that the strains produce compounds with  molecular masses in the range of 150–800 D, which belong  to different structural classes. In preliminary screening,  the Streptomyces sp. PU-MM93 showed high cytotoxicity  against two cancer cell lines (PC3 and A549). The chemical  screening of this strain revealed the reminiscent metabolic  diversity of Streptomyces. In this context we selected Strep- tomyces sp. PU-MM93 for scale-up fermentation and com- pounds purification to find the compounds responsible for  activity. The media optimization of this strain “PU-MM93”  revealed that culture medium and incubation time consid- erably influence the metabolites production and this strain  produce maximum metabolites on A-medium [32]. The purified bioactive compound 1 was identified as  aranciamycin which belongs to the structural class anthra- cyclines. Anthracyclines are essential chemotherapeutic  drugs and have been used frequently in treatment of breast  cancer, leukemia and solid tumors [33–35]. Aranciamycin  was first isolated and reported in 1970 by Keller Schi- erlein et al. from Streptomyces echinatus [36]. The pair  wise alignment of 16S rRNA gene sequence of the cur- rent  producer  strain Streptomyces  sp.  PU-MM93  with  that of Streptomyces echinatus NBRC  12763T showed  98.1% similarity, similarly comparison of the morpho- logical characteristics and growth pattern of the strains  suggested they are different species of genus Streptomy- ces.  Aranciamycin  and  its  derivatives  have  inhibitory

action  against  collagenase  which  is  instrumental  for  tumor metastasis and arthritis [37]. Aranciamycin also  has moderate antimicrobial activity against B. subtilis and  M. bovis BCG [38]. Isolated compound 2  was SM-173B  which also belongs to anthracyclines. It was first isolated  from S. chromofuscus SM-173 and reported by Fujiwara  et  al.  [39].  SM-173  antibiotic  has  been  reported  with  potent  activities  against  Gram-positive  bacteria  espe- cially S. aureus and Mycobacterium. Compound 3  was  identified as pactamycate which is a highly substituted  aminocyclopentanol-containing natural product. Pacta- mycate is structural congener of pactamycin which has  been reported with effective antimicrobial activity against  Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria along with  its potent cytotoxicity against various cancer cell lines  [40]. Oxachelin C (4) was also identified from the same  strain (Streptomyces sp. PU-MM93), which is classified  as peptide-salicylate natural product. Generally, they are  considered as chelating agents and well known for their  cytotoxicity against cancer cell lines, antibacterial and  antitrypanosomal activities. Oxachelin C was isolated  recently from Streptomyces sp. RM-14–6 and reported  by Shaaban et al. [41]. In their study, they reported that  oxachelin  C  is  a  potent  neuroprotective  agent.  Com- pound 5 was purified and identified as cyclo(L-Pro-L- Leu) which is classified as diketopiperazine molecule.  Cyclo(L-Pro-L-Leu) has been reported with broad range  of antibacterial, antiviral and antifungal activities [42].  Previously, cyclo(L-Pro-L-Leu) has also been reported  with nematicidal [43] and anti-leukemic activities [44].  It also inhibits the aflatoxin production by Aspergillus  parasiticus [45] and can be used as biosensor for quo- rum sensing [46]. The last compound isolated from our  Himalayan isolate Streptomyces PU-MM93

anti-leukemic activities [44].  It also inhibits the aflatoxin production by Aspergillus  parasiticus [45] and can be used as biosensor for quo- rum sensing [46]. The last compound isolated from our  Himalayan isolate Streptomyces PU-MM93 was identified  as  taurocholic  acid  (6)  and  it  is  also  known  as  choly- ltaurine or cholaic acid. Taurocholic acid (6) is a bile  acid and its isolation herein from microbial culture broth  is  very  interesting.  It’s  quite  possible  that  compound  6 might be produced as a result of bioconversion from  media components rather than a true secondary metabo- lite and produced due to the fermentative activity of the  strain Streptomyces PU-MM93. The A-medium used for  the fermentation of this strain contains peptone and yeast  extract, which is a routinely used media in our scale-up  studies of the Streptomyces strains, but this compound has  never been isolated from the broth culture of any other  strain previously. This opens an avenue for further studies  to investigate the microbial origin of this commercially  important  compound  by  isotopic  feeding  of  different  media components to the strain Streptomyces PU-MM93.  Taurocholic acid (6) is used as cholagogue agent which  promotes the discharge of bile and involves in emulsifica- tion of fats [47].

In summary, we have investigated the diversity and bio- technological potential of actinobacterial flora present in  the Himalayan region of Pakistan. The study revealed that  Streptomyces is most frequently present actinobacteria in  the region. The six pure compounds were isolated and iden- tified in scale-up screening of one of the selected strains,  among the isolated compounds, the compound 1 exhibited  moderate in vitro antitumor activity. In the present study,  we reported the first-time isolation of taurocholic acid (6)  from microbial origin. Overall, the isolated strains exhib- ited promising bioactivities along with the diverse chemical  profiles which signifies that continuous exploration from  this region may lead to the discovery of biologically active  and commercially important compounds.
